Foreign Minister of Armenia Ararat Mirzoyan had a phone conversation with Foreign Minister of Azerbaijan Jeyhun Bayramov. The Ministers exchanged views as a follow-up to the agreements reached by the leaders of both states. The parties agreed on the structure of the commission on delimitation and border security. It was agreed to convene a meeting on the commission on delimitation and border security in near future. The sides also discussed the issues related to addressing humanitarian issues, as well as preparation of peace talks.

Please show up for the midterms. Here is some info on when and where. Absentee voting: Absentee by-mail ballots are available to certain voters, including anyone age 60 and older and people who will be traveling outside their county during early voting and on Election Day. Early in-person voting: You can vote early and in person at your county election commission’s office or at a satellite early voting location, if your county uses one. Early voting runs from July 15 through July 30 for the primaries and Oct. 19 through Nov. 3 for the general election. In-person voting on Election Day: The state’s primary election is Thursday, Aug. 4; the general election is Tuesday, Nov. 8. Polling hours vary by county, but all locations will close at 7 p.m. CT, 8 p.m. ET.

Next up on our #PrideMonth Series is the iconic Harvey Milk. Milk was the first ever openly gay person to be elected to public office in the United States. Milk, who was Jewish, was a proponent of gay rights, civil rights, and cannabis legalization. Sadly, he was assassinated alongside San Francisco Mayor George Moscone in 1978 by a former political opponent. #Pride #LoveIsLove #Unity #LGBTQIA

DEVELOPMENTAL STAGES THE AFRICAN RENAISSANCE MOVEMENT~❤🖤💚 (Excerpt African Time) I. RESURRECTION: First, our collective memory must be restored so that we will understand what has happened to us and what must be done not only to improve this condition but to become what we should have been before we were side-tracked into thousands of seasons of White and Arab imposed slavery/servitude, carrying bags, crawling around converted, begging---a people being used and miss-used, hitched to the plow building the civilizations of others. We must study and prepare concrete, scientific knowledge of world history, and Africa's place in it. THIS IS THE WAKE-UP STAGE. II. REDEMPTION: Though modernized, we have fallen so much that we have nothing of substance that is our own. Our names, clothing, hair, languages, values, beliefs, religions, holidays, calendars, holy land, architecture, purposes in life---almost everything---we carbon copied from the White/Arab populations which enslaved our foremothers and fathers. Progressive African inner values, ethics, morals, and virtue must be restored by studying, improving, and implementing just African morals and behaviors. We redeem ourselves by respecting the best of what we were before we became something other than what we could, should, and still can become. We are more than what they have made us be. III. RECONSTRUCTION: Once we are awakened, cleansed, and organized to resolve the concrete problems that face us, we can stand-up like women and men in the face of any challenge in this life or the next. We must stop bending, we stop breaking, we stop lying down, and giving in at the hint of trouble. Then we will be on the path to being respected again. IV. RESTORATION: We reclaim our (1) African Self, (2) African Family, and (3) African Civilization by daily practical heroic deeds. We respect those who respect us, we care for our families, we prepare our best and our brightest, we defend those good in need, we stand tall facing all fear, we retake charge of our lives, we build in this life for the ages--again. V. REUNITE: UNITY, first, on the basis of color/culture, gender/sex, class, and age equality within the African population. Then break away from the oppressive/unjust world order of White/Arab over black, men over women, ruling capitalist class, old over new, and build within ourselves a higher, more humane African world order. We must build equality and justice from the ground up, relationship by relationship. VI. REBIRTH/RENAISSANCE: Give the Arabs and Whites their culture---their names, holidays, religions, clothing, hate of everything black, fraudulent histories, fake beliefs, languages, architecture, empty philosophies, hair weaves/straighteners, and other hate-care products, calendars, bad diets, and bad habits. Stand on the beautiful legacy of our ancient ancestors, before the invasions. Believe in Self, respect Self, defend Self, honor Self, and support Self. Spend every ounce of our energy, every second of our lives, every fiber of being, every moment rebuilding (stone by stone; person by person by person; institution by institution) a modernized/technologically advanced, morally sound, fiercely independent equally-founded African Civilization in our minds/morals first, then in Africa using the most advanced science and technology merged with Ancient African Kmt foundations of LIFE. THIS IS WHAT WE MUST DO. ***In addition to our 10:00 a.m. Easter celebration at Old South, we will have a 6:30 a.m. Easter sunrise service on Great Hill in North Weymouth. All are welcome!*** What a joy it will be to celebrate the Risen Lord together on Easter morning! At 10:00 a.m., we will gather in the sanctuary for a festive Easter service. The service will include a brass quartet, the adult choir, and the bell choir. We're pulling out all the stops! We'll hear the story of Easter morning as told to us in Luke 24:1-12, and we'll explore together how the resurrection helps us put our lives back together again. Easter is about “Re-membering Our Lives.” It will be good to worship together on Easter morning at 10:00 a.m., either in person or online! You can find our worship livestream right here on the Old South Union Church - Weymouth Facebook page. And you can find the order of the service below: * Words of Welcome * Prelude — Brass Preludes (Performed by Don Gorder, trumpet; Greg Hopkins, trumpet; Jeremy Ronkin, French horn; and A. Douglas Wauchope, trombone) * Greeting and Gathering for Worship * Opening Hymn — No. 289 "Christ the Lord is Risen Today" (https://files.ctctusercontent.com/730a4f31201/0ead2981-2072-4554-ae0b-bab4569bc73b.pdf?rdr=true) * Call to Worship * A Time of Prayer and the Lord's Prayer * Offering (You can give online here: http://oldsouthunion.org/donate/:=:https://oldsouthunion.org/donate/) * Offertory Anthem — A Jubilant Song (Allen Pote) * Doxology and Prayer of Dedication * Scripture — Luke 24:1-12 * Hymn — No. 295 "I Know That My Redeemer Lives" (https://files.ctctusercontent.com/730a4f31201/0ead2981-2072-4554-ae0b-bab4569bc73b.pdf?rdr=true) * Sermon — "Re-membering Our Lives" * Closing Hymn — No. 299 "He Lives" (https://files.ctctusercontent.com/730a4f31201/0ead2981-2072-4554-ae0b-bab4569bc73b.pdf?rdr=true) * Benediction * Postlude — Hallelujah! (G.F. Handel)

History has been made! Judge Ketanji Brown Jackson was just confirmed as the 116th Associate Justice of the United States Supreme Court. Not only do her dedication to fighting for human and civil rights and her deep commitment to equal justice make her eminently qualified to serve as a Supreme Court justice, but she is also the first Black woman and first former federal public defender to hold the nation’s highest court in its 232-year history. As we wait for the real work to begin, today we celebrate this groundbreaking achievement 🥳 ——————————— #repost @humanitycomm

Recently, 5 mothers living in Daykundi #Afghanistan told us of their struggles – about how hard it is to care for themselves and their children with so little resources. They shared their stories and their hopes for the future with us. “During my pregnancy I felt dizzy, and my whole body would start shaking. I then walked 2-2.5 hours on foot to get to a doctor. We were very concerned during my pregnancy about what will happen; will I reach the doctor in time or not? All the women here have the same concerns. Some manage to reach [a clinic] and some don't. We do not have enough food. We have very little. My hopes are that I have a good family, that I can reach to the clinic and the doctor in time so that my child is safe.” READ THE STORY: https://againsthunger.us/3BIm6yB:=:https://www.actionagainsthunger.org/story/afghanistan-voices-mothers

Our chief strategy officer Angelica Geter talks racism in the workplace with #CNBC and how we plan to tackle it. 👇🏾 When executives came to BWHI for guidance amid racial justice protests, “many said they had no idea racism was impacting Black and Brown people in this country, that the injustices were still happening in 2020, or the mental health effect of it all,” says Angelica Geter, chief strategy officer of the Black Women’s Health Imperative. BWHI brought together health professionals, business executives and community leaders to create a three-part workplace equity initiative, which launched to a pilot group in September 2021. The first piece is placing employers within a corporate equity index, which scores them based on current policies and practices and how they impact the health of employees, Geter explains. Next is developing corporate fairness training specific to each employer, aimed at “shifting workplace culture” to acknowledge and address how bias is built into the work environment and processes, Geter says. Finally, the equity initiative provides an anti-racism wellness toolkit for Black women with guidance on how to set boundaries at work, tap health resources and find other ways they can take care of themselves while navigating microaggressions in the workplace. Read more: https://www.cnbc.com/2022/02/17/how-companies-can-rebuild-workplaces-to-support-black-women.html #BWHIequity #DEI #WorkplaceEquity #HealthEquity #BlkWomensHealth

Nancy Elizabeth Prophet (1890-1960) Of African American and Native American descent, Prophet was born in Warwick, RI. Her father was a member of the Narragansett tribe and a city worker. Her mother was a cook, and both parents instilled in her a strong work ethic. Working as a domestic, Prophet saved her earnings in order to enter the Rhode Island School of Design in 1915, the first African American to do so, graduating in 1918. Prophet received commissions for her sculptured busts in Providence but soon turned again to domestic work in order to travel to France in 1922. Additional financial support came from fellow sculptor heiress Gertrude Vanderbilt Whitney. Prophet spent 12 years in Paris studying classical sculpture. Her work was accepted in several French salons, where she exhibited life-size figural works. W.E.B. Du Bois and Contee Cullen, Harlem Renaissance notables, and artist Henry O. Tanner helped her show her French work in the United States. She won a Harmon Foundation Prize for Sculpture in 1929. Prophet returned to America in 1932 and exhibited widely in Rhode Island, New York, and Pennsylvania. The Whitney Museum in New York acquired her work; one of the first by an African American to enter their collection. Two years later, Prophet moved to Atlanta and taught at Atlanta University, where Hale Woodruff taught, and later at Spelman College, where she expanded its curriculum to include art history and fine arts. Both Prophet and Woodruff considered it their “…responsibility to encourage students to portray black experience in their work.” Woodruff established an annual Atlanta art exhibition that became the most important venue for showcasing African American art. Discouraged by racial segregation that lingered in the South, Prophet returned to Rhode Island in 1945. She was unsuccessful in reigniting her art career, so she returned to domestic work. Near her death, she acknowledged her Native American descent, but refused to accept her African-American ancestry. Prophet’s Paris diary (1922 to 1934) is in the collection of the John Hay Library at Brown University, Providence, RI.

The two allegedly got into a verbal argument over the boy's sexuality when Julmeus found gay pornography on his phone. Julmeus "became very upset," according to the affidavit. Julmeus then allegedly took the boy to the Haines City Police Department, where he is said to have dropped him off on the side of the road in front of the building before heading back home. For Transgender Day of Visibility, we honor the cultural and social contributions of trans and gender non-conforming people. It is also important to acknowledge that not everyone is in a place to safely come out. They could be endangering their livelihoods, family and other relationships, or even their lives. We still celebrate those folks who can't come out right now; we still love and recognize you and support you and there is no shame in not coming out until it is safe and/or you're ready. Coming out as trans is particularly dangerous for BIPOC trans femmes, so we must recognize that it's a privilege to be able to come out and those who can do it safely are making it easier for those who can't right now. Trans and gender non-binary/gender non-conforming folks are a vital part of the Planned Parenthood community. We wanted to take a moment and tell our trans and gender non-conforming/non-binary staffers, patients, volunteers, friends, siblings, loved ones, and neighbors: We see you. We love and accept you. We proudly stand beside you. 🏳️‍⚧❤️🧡💛💚💙💜🖤🤍🤎

We're always thrilled when we see ASL-accessible queer events as well as Deaf LGBTQ hosted events taking place. We're also constantly bombarded with requests to help advertise these and other ASL accessible events on our social media platforms. We wish we could help everyone promote their events, but it's just not humanly possible. Every day, it's a struggle for us to just keep up with what we need to get done for DQRC with the limited time and resources we're currently working with. Posting an event announcement may seem like a simple task, but it often isn't. Oftentimes, the announcement doesn't include image description information if it's a graphic and we have to spend the labor of getting this from the submitter or writing it ourselves. Then there are folks who have questions about the event and think we're hosting it because we posted it, and we have to spend energy and labor responding to those questions, directing them to the right source, among many other things. The time and labor add up and we estimated it would require at least an additional 10-20 hours per week of time for us to be able to take on these requests for everyone that asks. That's time we just don't have. This is one of the reasons we created the Deaf Queers & Allies group here on Facebook. We ask folks to post their event and other announcements there. The group has over 5K members and it's a great way to reach the Deaf LGBTQ communities. We thank you for understanding. xo *** The following is a link to our Social Media Policy that was developed in March 2020 to address this issue: https://www.facebook.com/deafqueer/photos/a.3135332463172664/2879139868791926

More than 33 years after the Oscar-winning film “Rain Man” became one of the most influential onscreen depictions of autism spectrum disorder, a new Amazon Prime series is looking to widen the lens of autistic representation in the mainstream media. Based on the acclaimed Israeli comedy-drama series “On the Spectrum” and executive produced by Emmy-winner Jason Katims (“Friday Night Lights,” “Parenthood”), “As We See It” follows three 20-something roommates on the autism spectrum (played by Sue Ann Pien, Rick Glassman and Albert Rutecki). Pien plays Violet, who is known for always displaying and verbally processing every feeling she has. While Violet often feels like an outsider, her greatest desire is to have the perfect job and boyfriend, like most people in their 20s. “This is the most personal character that I’ve ever played in my entire life,” Pien, who has autism, told NBC Asian America. “The first time I read the breakdowns and the script, I cried because there were so many parallels between what she was going through and what I had to go through in my own life.” When she first received the audition material for “As We See It” in the middle of 2019, Pien, a Los Angeles native best known for being a former Mars One candidate, was struck by the show’s acute level of awareness and later discovered that Katims has a son with Asperger syndrome. “I think it’d be really hard for somebody who isn’t on the spectrum to portray these types of authentic moments of life that happen, that you can’t even describe unless you’ve been there,” Pien said. “Jason approaches this with so much love, and I can only imagine the father he is, and I know he has an incredible family. It was healing for me, as a person on the spectrum, but I hope for many, many families with loved ones on the spectrum or who are autistic themselves.” In a statement, Katims said he wanted to “live inside the experience of what it means to be on the autism spectrum, rather than take an outsider’s view,” which meant that it was imperative to cast the trio at the heart of the show as authentically as possible. Read more at NBCNews.com

Kareem Abdul-Jabbar (born Ferdinand Lewis Alcindor Jr.; April 16, 1947) is an American former professional basketball player who played 20 seasons in the National Basketball Association (NBA) for the Milwaukee Bucks and the Los Angeles Lakers. During his career as a center, Abdul-Jabbar was a record six-time NBA Most Valuable Player (MVP), a record 19-time NBA All-Star, a 15-time All-NBA selection, and an 11-time NBA All-Defensive Team member. A member of six NBA championship teams as a player and two more as an assistant coach, Abdul-Jabbar twice was voted NBA Finals MVP. He was named to the league's 35th, 50th and 75th anniversary teams. NBA coach Pat Riley and players Isiah Thomas and Julius Erving called him the greatest basketball player of all time. During the summer of 1968, Alcindor took the shahada twice and converted to Sunni Islam from Catholicism. He adopted the Arabic name Kareem Abdul-Jabbar, though he did not begin using it publicly until 1971.

#BlackHerstoryMonth starts TODAY! The perspectives of #BlackFeminists have consistently transformed the fights for gender equity and racial justice to ensure we can continue to build a world of equity, justice, and freedom for all. That’s why, all this month, we’re celebrating Black feminism and centering the work of powerful Black sheroes past and present doing the critical intersectional work to #EliminateRacism and #EmpowerWomen. Follow along all month long as we center the unsung legacy of Black feminism: from Jane Crow to Intersectionality.
